Steps to replicate:
# Add Story 1 to Epic A;
# Update Story 1 to belong to Epic B; 
# Perform the following JQL, the Story 1 will not appear:
{noformat}
project = abcd AND updated > "-5m"
{noformat}

P.S: 
- If you change any other information in Story 1, it will appear in the JQL;
- _updatedDate has the same result;

We need access to sprints and markers through the REST API.

Example:

GET /rest/greenhopper/1.0/api/board/1/sprint

{code}
[
      {
        "id": 2,
        "name": "Sample Sprint 2",
        "closed": true,
        "startDate": "25/Jan/13 5:46 AM",
        "endDate": "08/Feb/13 6:06 AM",
        "completeDate": "08/Feb/13 6:06 AM"
      },
      {
        "id": 3,
        "name": "Sample Sprint 3",
        "closed": false,
        "startDate": "25/Jan/13 5:46 AM",
        "endDate": "08/Feb/13 6:06 AM"
      },
      {
        "id": 4,
        "name": "Sample Sprint 4 (marker)",
        "closed": false,
        "afterIssueKey": "SSP-3"
      }
]
{code}

The timestamps have to be on a standard format (not included in the example). It would be fine if the not yet started sprints (markers) are accessible in other ways. But ultimately I think they should be part of the sprint data for the API consumer.

We need access to available boards from the REST API. It has to include id, name, filter, and whether it support scrum.

Example:

GET http://localhost:2990/jira/rest/greenhopper/1.0/api/board

{code}
[
    {
      "id": 1,
      "name": "Sample Scrum Project",
      "filter": 10000,
      "sprintSupportEnabled": true
    }
]
{code}

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Software Server*. Using *JIRA Software Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JSWCLOUD-7364].
